n of research, providing those new to the field with a thorough grounding. They highlight examples of interdisciplinary and transdisciplinary triumphs – and challenges. Concluding each chapter is a commentary provided by practitioners from diverse backgrounds, many of whom are themselves developing new approaches to inter- and transdisciplinarity. The book is: • the first ever comprehensive reader for interdisciplinarity and transdisciplinarity; • essential reading for those seeking to become effective collaborative researchers; • complete with concise introductions, extracts, commentary and further reading in each chapter. This is a much-needed primer that improves our understanding of the characteristics of interdisciplinarity and transdisciplinarity, unlocking their exciting potential in research and teaching within and beyond academia. Introduction chapter is available Open Access under CC-BY-NC-ND licence.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Methodology.2bisacsh1 aBurgess, Maureen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCheas, Kirsi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDupin, Nathalie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFletcher, Isabel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFletcher, Isabel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLyall, Catherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLyall, Catherine, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aOhlmeyer, Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPohl, Christian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStuder, Sibylle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVienni-Bapti